    "Through active exploration, such projects prompt secondary school students to contemplate the personal, social, economic, and ethical consequences of AI technologies (Kaspersen et al., 2021).",
    "Second, collaborative learning allows students to work in groups to promote cognitive knowledge, as it engages them in scientific inquiry with the help of smart devices (Wan et al., 2020).",
    "Kaspersen et al. (2021) designed a collaborative learning tool, VotestratesML, together with a voting project allowing students to build machine learning models based on real-world voting data to predict results.",
    "Of the 46 articles, 31 reported potential learning outcomes: (1) cognitive outcomes, (2) affective and behavioral outcomes, and (3) the level of course satisfaction and soft skills acquisition.",
    "Thirty-one studies documented various degrees of positive cognitive outcomes."
